post_cb({"32785675": {"ViewCount": "1072", "Body": "<p>The standard C++ [3.9.1-1] says that</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_32785675_32785675_0\">For unsigned character types, all possible bit patterns of the value representation represent numbers. </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The standard [18.3.2.4-(comment 197)] also says that the maximum value of unsigned char are equivalent to <code>UCHAR_MAX</code> in C, which is defined as 255 in C standard [5.2.4.2.1]. So does this mean the size of unsigned char type in C++ is exactly 8 bits?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "32785794", "Title": "About the size of unsigned char type in C++", "CreationDate": "2015-09-25T15:30:18.993", "Id": "32785675", "CommentCount": "2", "LastEditDate": "2015-09-25T15:50:50.220", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "4342498", "LastActivityDate": "2015-09-25T17:21:28.903", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "5376789", "Tags": "<c++>", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_32785675_32785675_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "section_id": 7210}}, "n3337": {"so_32785675_32785675_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "section_id": 6954}}, "n4659": {"so_32785675_32785675_0": {"length": 8, "quality": 0.6666666666666666, "section_id": 8719}}}, "32785794": {"Id": "32785794", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>From C11 5.2.4.2.1</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_32785675_32785794_0\">The values given below shall be replaced by constant expressions suitable for use in #if\n  preprocessing directives. Moreover, except for CHAR_BIT and MB_LEN_MAX, the\n  following shall be replaced by expressions that have the same type as would an\n  expression that is an object of the corresponding type converted according to the integer\n  promotions. <strong>Their implementation-defined values shall be equal or greater in magnitude (absolute value) to those shown, with the same sign.</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><sup>(emphasis mine)</sup></p>\n<p>So the standard defines that at a minimum <code>UCHAR_MAX</code> needs to be 255 but it can be greater than that.</p>\n<p>The guarantees that we have on size are:</p>\n<pre><code>sizeof(char) = 1 and sizeof(char) &lt;= sizeof(short) &lt;= sizeof(int) &lt;= sizeof(long) &lt;= sizeof(long long)\n</code></pre>\n<p>And at a minimum the signed versions of the data types must be able to hold:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>char      [-127, 127]</code></li>\n<li><code>short     [-32767, 32767]</code></li>\n<li><code>int       [-32767, 32767]</code></li>\n<li><code>long      [-2147483647, 2147483647]</code></li>\n<li><code>long long [-9223372036854775807, 9223372036854775807]</code></li>\n</ul>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "4342498", "LastActivityDate": "2015-09-25T17:21:28.903", "Score": "9", "CreationDate": "2015-09-25T15:36:53.933", "ParentId": "32785675", "CommentCount": "10", "OwnerUserId": "4342498", "LastEditDate": "2015-09-25T17:21:28.903"}});